st Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:FA Cup winners]]\n[[Category:1908 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:North Eastern League]]\n[[Category:Premier League clubs]]\n[[Category:Midland Football League (1889)]]\n[[Category:Former English Football League clubs]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{for|the women's team|Huddersfield Town Women F.C.}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| current = 2019\u201320 Huddersfield Town A.F.C. season\n| clubname = Huddersfield Town A.F.C.\n| image = Huddersfield Town A.F.C. logo.png\n| image_size = 150px\n| fullname = Huddersfield Town Association Football Club\n| nickname = The Terriers\n| founded = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1908|8|15}}\n| ground = [[Kirklees Stadium]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|53|39|15.0361|N|1|46|5.8605|W|type:landmark_region:GB_scale:2000|display=it}}\n| capacity = 24,121<ref>{{cite news|title=VIEWING PLATFORM FOR AWAY SUPPORTERS|url=https://www.htafc.com/news/2017/november/viewing-platform-for-away-supporters/|accessdate=3 November 2017|publisher=Huddersfield Town AFC|date=3 November 2017}}</ref>\n| chairman = Phil Hodgkinson\n| manager = [[Danny Cowley]]\n| league = {{English football updater|HuddersT}}\n| season = {{English football updater|HuddersT2}}\n| position = {{English football updater|HuddersT3}}\n| website = https://www.htafc.com/\n| pattern_la1 = _huddersfield1920h\n| pattern_b1 = _huddersfield1920h\n| pattern_ra1 = _huddersfield1920h\n| pattern_sh1 = _huddersfield1920h\n| pattern_so1 = _huddersfield1920h\n| leftarm1 = 0000FF\n| body1 = FFFFFF\n| rightarm1 = 0000FF\n| shorts1 = FFFFFF\n| socks1 = FFFFFF\n| pattern_la2 = _huddersfield1920a\n| pattern_b2 = _huddersfield1920a\n| pattern_ra2 = _huddersfield1920a\n| pattern_sh2 = _huddersfield1920a\n| pattern_so2 = _huddersfield1920a\n| leftarm2 = 000088\n| body2 = 000088\n| rightarm2 = 000088\n| shorts2 = 000088\n| socks2 = 000088\n| pattern_la3 = _huddersfield1920t\n| pattern_b3 = _huddersfield1920t\n| pattern_ra3 = _huddersfield1920t\n| pattern_sh3 = _huddersfield1920t\n| pattern_so3 = _huddersfield1920t\n| leftarm3 = FF7F50\n| body3 = FF7F50\n| rightarm3 = FF7F50\n| shorts3 = FF7F50\n| socks3 = FF7F50\n}}\n'''Huddersfield Town Association Football Club''' is a professional [[association football|football]] club in [[Huddersfield]], [[West Yorkshire]], England, which competes in the [[EFL Championship|Championship]].\n\nHuddersfield became the first English club to win three successive [[List of English football champions|English League titles]] in 1926, a feat which only three other clubs have matched. The first two league titles were won under legendary manager and pioneer [[Herbert Chapman]], who also led the club to an [[FA Cup]] win in [[1922 FA Cup Final|1922]]. In the late 1950s the club was managed by [[Bill Shankly]] and featured [[Denis Law]] and [[Ray Wilson (English footballer)|Ray Wilson]]. Following relegation from the [[Football League First Division|First Division]] in 1972, Huddersfield spent 45 years in the second, third and fourth tiers of English football, before returning to the top flight in 2017. They were relegated back to the [[Championship]] at the end of the 2018\u201319 season.\n\n==History==\n{{Main article|History of Huddersfield Town A.F.C.}}\n\n[[File:Huddersfield Town FC League Performance.svg|thumb|right|250px|Chart showing the progress of Huddersfield Town A.F.C. through the [[English football league system]].]]In 1910, just three years after being founded, Huddersfield entered [[the Football League]] for the first time. In November 1919 a fund-raising campaign was needed to avoid a move to [[Leeds]]. Citizens of Huddersfield were asked to buy shares in the club for \u00a31 each, and the club staved off the proposed merger. The team went on to reach the [[1920 FA Cup Final]] and win promotion to [[Football League First Division|Division One]].\n\nHuddersfield became the first English team to win three successive [[List of English football champions|English League titles]] in 1926 \u2013 a feat that only three other clubs ([[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]) have been able to match \u2013 and was achieved under the leadership of legendary manager and pioneer [[Herbert Chapman]] and his successor [[Cecil Potter]]. Huddersfield Town also won the [[FA Cup]] in [[1922 FA Cup Final|1922]] and the [[FA Community Shield|Charity Shield]] the same year and have been runners-up on four other occasions in the FA Cup. During the club's heyday in the 1920s and 1930s, they achieved a record attendance of 67,037 on 27 February 1932 during their FA Cup 6th round tie against Arsenal at [[Leeds Road]]. This attendance has been bettered by only 13 other clubs in the history of the Football League.\n\nAfter the [[Second World War]], the club began a gradual decline, losing its [[Football League First Division|First Division]] status in [[1951\u201352 Football League|1952]]. They came straight back up, but were relegated again three seasons later. Before the start of the [[1969\u201370 Huddersfield Town A.F.C. season|1969\u201370]] season, Huddersfield Town adopted the nickname \"''The Terriers''\". They won the Second Division title that season, spending the next two seasons in the top flight. After that they moved up and down through the lower three divisions for 45 years.\n\nIn 1998, the club attracted the attention of local businessman Barry Rubery and, after protracted takeover talks, he took over the running of the club, promising significant investment as the club sought [[Premier League|Premiership]] status. However, the club did not make it back to the top flight and fell two divisions. The club was sold by Rubery to David Taylor and under Taylor's ownership, slipped into administration. In the summer of 2003, the Terriers came out of administration under the new ownership of [[Ken Davy]].\n\nIn [[2010\u201311 Huddersfield Town A.F.C. season|2010\u201311]], Huddersfield went 43 games unbeaten, the second-highest in the league after [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal's]] 49-match run of 2003\u201304.<ref>{{cite news |title=Huddersfield's record run ends after 43 matches |url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-soccer-england-huddersfield/huddersfields-record-run-ends-after-43-matches-idUKTRE7AS0HS20111129 |website=Reuters |agency=Reuters |accessdate=19 December 2018|date=29 November 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn 26 May 2012, following a penalty shoot-out in the [[2012 Football League One play-off Final]] victory over [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]], Huddersfield were promoted to the [[EFL Championship|Championship]]. The shoot-out was the longest contested in the current League One play-offs format.  After eleven rounds, the final score was 8\u20137 to Huddersfield, with the winning goal being scored by goalkeeper [[Alex Smithies]]. Huddersfield missed the first three penalties became the first team to win an football league play-off penalty shootout after doing so.\n\nIn November 2015, German-born ex-[[United States men's national soccer team|US international]] [[David Wagner (soccer)|David Wagner]] was appointed head coach, becoming the first person born outside the [[British Isles]] to manage the club in their 107-year history.<ref>{{cite news |title=David Wagner named new Huddersfield Town head coach |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34733422 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=19 December 2018|date=5 November 2015 }}</ref>\n\nOn 29 May 2017, the club successfully earned promotion to the [[Premier League]] for the first time (since the rebranding in 1992) and the English top flight for the first time since [[1971\u201372 Football League|1972]], beating [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] 4\u20133 on penalties following a 0\u20130 draw after extra time in the [[2017 EFL Championship play-off Final|Championship play-off Final]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Huddersfield Town 0 -0 Reading (4-3 Pens) |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39995791 |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |accessdate=19 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 May 2018, the club secured safety from relegation, earning another season in the Premier League, following a 1\u20131 draw against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] and went on to place 16th.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Chelsea 1\u20131 Huddersfield Town | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 9 May 2018 | accessdate = 9 May 2018 | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43971368 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180508144829/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43971368 | archive-date = 8 May 2018 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> However, the club suffered a very poor start to the 2018-19 season, taking just 2 wins in their first 22 matches. With the team rooted to the bottom of the table with just 11 points on the board, Wagner left the club by mutual consent on 14 January 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46864005|title=David Wagner: Huddersfield Town manager leaves club by mutual consent|date=14 January 2019|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> He was replaced with former [[Borussia Dortmund II]] manager [[Jan Siewert]] on a 2 year deal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46943388|title=Huddersfield Town appoint Jan Siewert from Borussia Dortmund as new manager|date=21 January 2019|via=www.bbc.co.uk|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> However, he couldn't prevent Huddersfield suffering relegation from the Premier League on 30 March 2019 following a defeat to [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]], with the club joining [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] and [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] as the only clubs in the league's history to be relegated with six matches left to play.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47676513|title=Crystal Palace 2-0 Huddersfield: Terriers' relegation confirmed at Selhurst Park|date=30 March 2019|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nAfter failing to win any of the first 3 matches of the 2019\u201320 season, Siewert was sacked in August after just 7 months in charge.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49319183 | title=Jan Siewert: Huddersfield Town sack head coach after one win in seven months| work=BBC Sport| date=16 August 2019}}</ref> He was replaced by Lincoln City boss [[Danny Cowley]] on 9 September.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49634696 | title=Danny Cowley: Huddersfield Town appoint Lincoln City boss as manager| work=BBC Sport| date=9 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Badge and colours==\nThe club spent over five years debating what colour the kit should be. It ranged from [[salmon pink]] to plain white or all-blue to white with blue [[yoke]]. Eventually in [[Huddersfield Town F.C. season 1913\u201314|1913]], the club adopted the blue-and-white jersey that remains to this day.\n\nThe club badge is based on the [[coat of arms]] of Huddersfield. Town first used a badge on its shirts for the [[1920 FA Cup Final]] based on the local Huddersfield Corporation coat of arms. It appeared again with a [[Yorkshire Rose]] for the [[1922 FA Cup Final]] and again for the finals of [[1928 FA Cup Final|1928]], [[1930 FA Cup Final|1930]] and [[1938 FA Cup Final|1938]]. The club's main [[color|colours]] (blue and white) are evident throughout the badge both in the [[mantling]] and in the [[shield]], in the form of stripes. Two Yorkshire White Roses and [[Castle Hill, Huddersfield|Castle Hill]] form part of the history of the club and the area.\n\nTown stuck with the same principal design (blue and white stripes) until [[Huddersfield Town F.C. season 1966\u201367|1966]], when [[Scotland|Scottish]] manager [[Tom Johnston (footballer)|Tom Johnston]] introduced all-blue shirts. The next badge did not feature until the [[Huddersfield Town F.C. season 1966\u201367|1966\u201367 season]], when the simple \"HTFC\" adorned the Town's all-blue shirts.\n\nWhen the club adopted the nickname \"The Terriers\" for the [[Huddersfield Town F.C. season 1969\u201370|1969\u201370 season]], the blue and white stripes returned and with it a red terrier with the words \"The Terriers\", just in time for their promotion to the big time, the [[Football League First Division|First Division]]. The [[Yorkshire terrier|terrier]] sits on top of the crest with a [[ball]] on a blanket of blue and white stripes. The Terriers was introduced to the badge shortly after \"The Terriers\" was adopted as the nickname and [[mascot]] of the club.\n\nAfter relegation to the [[Football League Fourth Division|Fourth Division]], Town returned to all-blue shirts with the return of Tom Johnston in [[Huddersfield Town F.C. season 1975\u201376|1975]]. This time they only lasted two seasons and the return of simply \"HTFC\" badge. This lasted from [[Huddersfield Town F.C. season 1975\u201376|1975]]\u2013[[Huddersfield Town F.C. season 1976\u201377|1977]]. Stripes returned from [[Huddersfield Town F.C. season 1977\u201378|the 1977\u201378 season]] and has been the club's home kit ever since. The red Terrier returned to the shirt for [[Huddersfield Town F.C. season 1978\u201379|the 1978\u201379 season]]. In 1980, Town adopted what remains their badge today based on the coat of arms of Huddersfield. This is both the club badge and playing shirt badge and is held in high esteem by Town fans.\n\nIn 2000, Town changed badge to a circular design, but that was never popular and following a change of board, returned to the heraldic-style badge. The badge was further redeveloped with a small but significant adaptation in February 2005. The club took the decision to remove \"A.F.C.\" from the text leaving only the wording 'Huddersfield Town'. The current board said that this was in keeping with the time and to make merchandise easier to produce and to make slicker looking promotional material.\n\nTo mark Town's promotion to the [[Premier League]] in 2017-18, the club adopted a Terriers logo to replace the historic crest on the shirts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.examiner.co.uk/news/huddersfield-town-mascot-terry-terrier-13433906|title=Town mascot Terry the Terrier gets a makeover in time for Premier League debut|first=Tony|last=Earnshaw|date=5 August 2017|website=huddersfieldexaminer}}</ref>\n\nTo mark Town's relegation from the [[Premier League]] in 2019, the club agreed to have [[Paddy Power]] shirt sponsorship in a striking beauty queen style diagonal sash design.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/htafc/status/1151401159011315718|title=#htafc's new home kit for the upcoming 2019/20 season has today been revealed! Produced by main supplier @UmbroUK, the new home kit features a modern spin on the traditional blue and white striped home shirt thanks to new title sponsor @paddypower.|first=Huddersfield|last=Town|date=17 July 2019}}</ref> Within days, the club were contacted by [[The Football Association]] for their 'observations' about the kit.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/49026053|title=Huddersfield Town: Football Association requests club's 'observations' over 2019-20 kit|date=17 July 2019|via=www.bbc.com|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> Shortly it was revealed that the \"sash\" shirt was a prank envisioned by Paddy Power, and that the club would play in shirts without a sponsor.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.examinerlive.co.uk/sport/football/news/huddersfield-town-kit-confirmed-prank-16599687|title=Actual Huddersfield Town kit revealed - with no sponsor|last=Chicken|first=Steven|date=2019-07-19|website=huddersfieldexaminer|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n\n==Stadium==\n*[[Leeds Road]] (1908\u20131994)\n[[File:Galpharm Stadium - geograph.org.uk - 312658.jpg|thumb|[[Kirklees Stadium]]]]\n*[[Kirklees Stadium]] (1994\u2013present)\n**Named \"''Alfred McAlpine Stadium''\" (1994\u20132004)\n**Named \"''Galpharm Stadium''\" (2004\u20132012)\n**Named \"''John Smith's Stadium''\" (2012\u2013present)\n\nHuddersfield are the only team to have played at each of the top four levels of English football at two different grounds.<ref>{{Cite episode\n | series         = [[Match of the Day]]\n | network        = BBC\n | station        = BBC One HD\n | date           = 4 November 2017\n | minutes        = 73\n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fchd.info/HUDDERST.HTM|title=HUDDERSFIELD TOWN|accessdate=28 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602064602/http://fchd.info/HUDDERST.HTM|archive-date=2 June 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Rivalries==\n{{main article|West Yorkshire derby}}\n\n[[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] are considered to be the club's main rivals, with Huddersfield having the better head-to-head record of the two teams.  Including games against [[Leeds United F.C.|United's]] predecessor club [[Leeds City F.C.|Leeds City]], Huddersfield have won 36 of the 88 derbies between the two sides with 20 draws and 32 Leeds wins.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/teams/head_to_head.sd?team_id=1524&team2_id=1309|title=Bet on Leeds vs Huddersfield {{!}} Soccer Base|website=www.soccerbase.com|access-date=4 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180516103500/http://www.soccerbase.com/teams/head_to_head.sd?team_id=1524&team2_id=1309|archive-date=16 May 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Huddersfield's other fierce local rivals are [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]; this is due to both clubs having had roughly the same league status for the last couple of decades and therefore it could be argued that they are closest rivals out of the three West Yorkshire teams.  Huddersfield also have the better head-to-head record between the two, winning 21 derbies with 17 draws and 14 Bradford wins.\n\nThere are smaller rivalries with [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] (31 wins, 15 draws, 26 defeats), [[A62 Derby|Roses]] rivals [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]] (20 wins, 15 draws, 12 defeats) and formerly with near neighbours [[Halifax Town A.F.C.|Halifax Town]] (8 wins, 5 draws, 4 defeats). [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] were also once considered rivals during the time that the two clubs were competing in the old First Division - Manchester City lead in the head-to-heads, however, with 28 victories to Huddersfield's 22, with 30 drawn games between them.\n<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.examinerlive.co.uk/sport/football/news/huddersfield-town-fans-consider-leeds-16716362 |title = Town fans consider Leeds main rivals - but feeling isn't mutual|date = 7 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nA survey conducted as recently as August 2019 showed that Huddersfield supporters consider [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]], [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] and [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]] to be their fiercest rivals, with [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] and [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] following.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.givemesport.com/1500300-the-top-five-rivals-of-english-footballs-top-92-clubs-revealed |title = The top five rivals of English football's top 92 clubs have been revealed|date = 27 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Affiliated clubs==\n\n* {{Flagicon|England}} [[Huddersfield Town Women F.C.]]\n* {{Flagicon|England}} [[Yorkshire County Cricket Club]]\n\n==Sponsors==\n\n===Main club sponsors and kit suppliers===\nThe main club sponsors also have the right to have their identity on the shirts.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"color:white; background:#0072ce;\"|Season(s)\n! style=\"color:white; background:#0072ce;\"|Kit supplier\n! style=\"color:white; background:#0072ce;\"|Club Sponsor\n|-\n| 1975\u20131979 || |[[Bukta]]  || rowspan=\"2\"|''none''\n|-\n| 1979\u20131982 || |Barralan\n|-\n| 1982\u20131984 || rowspan=\"2\"|[[Bukta]] ||  Central [[Mirfield]]\n|-\n| 1984\u20131986 || [[Daihatsu]]\n|-\n| 1986\u20131987 || Eagle || rowspan=\"3\"|[[De Vere Group|Greenall's]]\n|-\n| 1987\u20131989 || Matchwinner \u3000\n|-\n| 1989\u20131991 || Beaver\n|-\n| 1991\u20131993 || [[Gola (manufacturer)|Gola]] || Gola\n|-\n| 1993\u20131994 || rowspan=\"3\"|